  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is the primary purpose of rclpy in ROS 2?","answer":"It is the Python client library for ROS 2.","reasoning":"rclpy provides APIs to create nodes, publishers, subscribers, services, and actions in Python."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"Why must rclpy.init() be called before creating ROS 2 nodes?","answer":"It initializes the ROS 2 communication layer.","reasoning":"Without initialization, DDS middleware is not set up and nodes cannot communicate."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What does rclpy.spin(node) do?","answer":"It keeps the node alive and processes callbacks.","reasoning":"Spin blocks execution while handling timers, subscriptions, services, and actions."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is a ROS 2 node?","answer":"A single process that performs computation and communicates over topics, services, or actions.","reasoning":"Nodes are the fundamental execution units in ROS 2."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"Why should a ROS 2 node have a unique name?","answer":"To avoid name collisions in the ROS graph.","reasoning":"Duplicate names can override or interfere with existing nodes."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"How do you create a publisher in ROS 2 Python?","answer":"Using node.create_publisher(MessageType, topic_name, qos).","reasoning":"Publishers send messages to a named topic with a defined QoS."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"How do you create a subscriber in ROS 2 Python?","answer":"Using node.create_subscription(MessageType, topic_name, callback, qos).","reasoning":"Subscribers receive messages asynchronously via callbacks."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is a topic in ROS 2?","answer":"A named channel for streaming messages.","reasoning":"Topics enable decoupled many-to-many communication."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"Why are ROS 2 topics strongly typed?","answer":"To ensure message compatibility and safety.","reasoning":"Publishers and subscribers must agree on message structure."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What happens if QoS settings do not match between publisher and subscriber?","answer":"They may not communicate at all.","reasoning":"DDS requires compatible QoS profiles to establish communication."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What does QoS depth control?","answer":"The size of the message queue.","reasoning":"It determines how many messages are stored if callbacks lag."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is Reliability QoS?","answer":"It controls whether messages must be delivered reliably or can be dropped.","reasoning":"Reliable ensures delivery; BestEffort prioritizes latency."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is Durability QoS?","answer":"It controls whether late subscribers receive old messages.","reasoning":"TransientLocal allows late joiners to get last published data."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What QoS is typically used for /cmd_vel?","answer":"Reliable with small depth.","reasoning":"Control commands must be delivered consistently."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What QoS is commonly used for camera topics?","answer":"BestEffort with small depth.","reasoning":"Dropping frames is preferable to latency buildup."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is a ROS 2 timer?","answer":"A mechanism to run callbacks periodically.","reasoning":"Timers drive loops without manual while-loops."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"Why are timers preferred over while loops in ROS 2?","answer":"They integrate with the executor safely.","reasoning":"While loops can block callback processing."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is an executor in ROS 2?","answer":"It schedules and executes callbacks.","reasoning":"Executors manage concurrency in nodes."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is the default executor in rclpy?","answer":"SingleThreadedExecutor.","reasoning":"Callbacks run sequentially by default."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"When would you use MultiThreadedExecutor?","answer":"When callbacks are independent and blocking.","reasoning":"Allows parallel execution of callbacks."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is a ROS 2 service?","answer":"A synchronous request-response communication pattern.","reasoning":"Used for quick commands or queries."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"How does a service differ from a topic?","answer":"Services are synchronous; topics are asynchronous.","reasoning":"Services block until a response is received."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is a ROS 2 action?","answer":"An asynchronous long-running task with feedback.","reasoning":"Actions support goals, feedback, and results."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"Why use actions instead of services for navigation?","answer":"Navigation is long-running and cancellable.","reasoning":"Actions provide progress feedback and cancellation."},
