  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What color order does OpenCV use by default?","answer":"BGR.","reasoning":"OpenCV stores color images as Blue-Green-Red, not RGB."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert BGR to RGB in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB).","reasoning":"Many ML libraries and plotting tools expect RGB."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert BGR to grayscale?","answer":"cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY).","reasoning":"Reduces channels and often simplifies downstream processing."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert grayscale back to BGR for drawing colored overlays?","answer":"cv2.cvtColor(gray, cv2.COLOR_GRAY2BGR).","reasoning":"Drawing colored shapes requires 3-channel images."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you get an imageâ€™s height and width from a NumPy array?","answer":"h,w = img.shape:2].","reasoning":"Color images include channels in img.shape2]."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you resize an image to fixed dimensions?","answer":"cv2.resize(img,(new_w,new_h)).","reasoning":"OpenCV expects (width,height) order."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you resize while keeping aspect ratio based on target width?","answer":"scale=target_w/w; new_h=int(h*scale); cv2.resize(img,(target_w,new_h)).","reasoning":"Scaling preserves geometry and avoids distortion."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you choose an interpolation method for shrinking images?","answer":"Use cv2.INTER_AREA.","reasoning":"INTER_AREA is generally best for downsampling."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you choose an interpolation method for enlarging images?","answer":"Use cv2.INTER_LINEAR or cv2.INTER_CUBIC.","reasoning":"These reduce blockiness when upscaling."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you crop an ROI using NumPy slicing?","answer":"roi = imgy1:y2, x1:x2].","reasoning":"NumPy uses row-major indexing: y, x]."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you safely clip crop coordinates to image bounds?","answer":"Clamp x/y to 0,w) and 0,h) before slicing.","reasoning":"Prevents empty or out-of-range slices."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you rotate an image 90 degrees clockwise in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.rotate(img, cv2.ROTATE_90_CLOCKWISE).","reasoning":"Built-in rotate avoids manual affine math."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you rotate an image by an arbitrary angle around center?","answer":"M=cv2.getRotationMatrix2D(center,angle,scale); cv2.warpAffine(img,M,(w,h)).","reasoning":"Affine warping applies rotation via a transform matrix."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you flip an image horizontally?","answer":"cv2.flip(img, 1).","reasoning":"flipCode=1 mirrors left-right."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you flip vertically?","answer":"cv2.flip(img, 0).","reasoning":"flipCode=0 mirrors top-bottom."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you normalize pixel values to 0..1 for ML input?","answer":"img_f = img.astype('float32')/255.0.","reasoning":"Float conversion avoids integer truncation."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why convert uint8 images to float before dividing?","answer":"To prevent integer truncation and keep decimals.","reasoning":"uint8 division can yield unexpected results without casting."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply Gaussian blur in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.GaussianBlur(img,(k,k),sigma).","reasoning":"Gaussian blur reduces noise and smooths edges."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What kernel size constraint applies to GaussianBlur?","answer":"Kernel size should be odd and positive.","reasoning":"Odd kernels have a defined center pixel."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply median blur?","answer":"cv2.medianBlur(img, k).","reasoning":"Median filtering is effective for salt-and-pepper noise."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply bilateral filtering?","answer":"cv2.bilateralFilter(img, d, sigmaColor, sigmaSpace).","reasoning":"It smooths while preserving edges better than Gaussian."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you run Canny edge detection?","answer":"edges=cv2.Canny(gray,t1,t2).","reasoning":"Thresholds control edge sensitivity and noise rejection."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why does Canny typically use a grayscale image?","answer":"Edges are intensity-based; grayscale simplifies gradients.","reasoning":"Color channels complicate gradient computation."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute Sobel gradients in x direction?","answer":"cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0, ksize=3).","reasoning":"Sobel computes derivatives; 1,0 means dx only."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute magnitude from Sobel dx and dy?","answer":"mag = np.sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy).","reasoning":"Gradient magnitude combines x and y derivatives."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you threshold an image with a fixed threshold?","answer":"_,mask=cv2.threshold(gray,t,255,cv2.THRESH_BINARY).","reasoning":"threshold returns threshold used and the binary output."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you use Otsu thresholding?","answer":"_,mask=cv2.threshold(gray,0,255,cv2.THRESH_BINARY+cv2.THRESH_OTSU).","reasoning":"Otsu computes an optimal threshold automatically."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you perform adaptive thresholding?","answer":"cv2.adaptiveThreshold(gray,255,method,type,blockSize,C).","reasoning":"Adaptive methods handle uneven lighting better."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you erode a binary mask?","answer":"cv2.erode(mask, kernel, iterations=n).","reasoning":"Erosion shrinks foreground regions and removes small noise."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you dilate a binary mask?","answer":"cv2.dilate(mask, kernel, iterations=n).","reasoning":"Dilation expands foreground regions and fills gaps."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is morphological opening?","answer":"Erosion followed by dilation.","reasoning":"Opening removes small foreground noise."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply opening in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.morphologyEx(mask, cv2.MORPH_OPEN, kernel).","reasoning":"morphologyEx implements combined morphological ops."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is morphological closing?","answer":"Dilation followed by erosion.","reasoning":"Closing fills small holes in foreground objects."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply closing in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.morphologyEx(mask, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel).","reasoning":"Useful to close gaps and holes after thresholding."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you create a rectangular structuring element?","answer":"cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_RECT,(k,k)).","reasoning":"Kernel shape affects morphological behavior."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you find contours in a binary image?","answer":"contours,_=cv2.findContours(mask, mode, method).","reasoning":"Contours represent connected boundaries in binary masks."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why can cv2.findContours require a copy of the mask?","answer":"It may modify the source image.","reasoning":"Using mask.copy() avoids altering original data."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you draw contours on an image?","answer":"cv2.drawContours(img, contours, -1, color, thickness).","reasoning":"drawContours overlays boundary shapes for visualization."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute a bounding rectangle for a contour?","answer":"x,y,w,h=cv2.boundingRect(cnt).","reasoning":"boundingRect returns axis-aligned bounding box."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute a minimum-area rotated rectangle?","answer":"rect=cv2.minAreaRect(cnt).","reasoning":"minAreaRect provides oriented bounding boxes."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you get corner points from minAreaRect?","answer":"box=cv2.boxPoints(rect); box=np.intp(box).","reasoning":"boxPoints converts rect to 4 corner coordinates."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute contour area?","answer":"area=cv2.contourArea(cnt).","reasoning":"Area is useful for filtering small blobs."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you filter contours by area in Python?","answer":"keep=c for c in contours if cv2.contourArea(c)>min_area].","reasoning":"Removes noise and tiny detections."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute contour perimeter?","answer":"per=cv2.arcLength(cnt, True).","reasoning":"Arc length measures boundary length."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you approximate contours to polygons?","answer":"approx=cv2.approxPolyDP(cnt, eps, True).","reasoning":"Approximations simplify shapes for detection (e.g., rectangles)."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute image histogram in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.calcHist(gray],0],None,256],0,256]).","reasoning":"Histograms help analyze intensity distributions."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you equalize histogram of a grayscale image?","answer":"eq=cv2.equalizeHist(gray).","reasoning":"Equalization improves contrast in low-contrast images."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply CLAHE?","answer":"clahe=cv2.createCLAHE(clipLimit, tileGridSize); out=clahe.apply(gray).","reasoning":"CLAHE boosts local contrast without over-amplifying noise."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert BGR to HSV?","answer":"hsv=cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV).","reasoning":"HSV separates color (hue) from brightness (value), aiding segmentation."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you threshold a color range in HSV?","answer":"mask=cv2.inRange(hsv, lower, upper).","reasoning":"inRange returns a binary mask for selected hues/saturation/value."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you combine two masks in OpenCV?","answer":"mask=cv2.bitwise_or(mask1,mask2).","reasoning":"Bitwise operations combine binary masks efficiently."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply a mask to an image?","answer":"out=cv2.bitwise_and(img,img,mask=mask).","reasoning":"bitwise_and keeps pixels where mask is nonzero."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you add two images with clipping in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.add(img1,img2).","reasoning":"cv2.add saturates at 255 and avoids overflow wrap."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why can using NumPy + overflow on uint8 be a bug?","answer":"It wraps modulo 256.","reasoning":"np.uint8(250)+np.uint8(10) wraps to 4; cv2.add saturates."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you blend two images with alpha?","answer":"cv2.addWeighted(a,alpha,b,1-alpha,gamma).","reasoning":"Weighted sum produces smooth blending."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert an OpenCV image to PIL format?","answer":"Convert BGR->RGB then Image.fromarray(rgb).","reasoning":"PIL expects RGB arrays for correct colors."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert a PIL image to OpenCV?","answer":"np.array(pil) then RGB->BGR.","reasoning":"Ensures channel order matches OpenCV expectations."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you capture frames from a webcam in OpenCV?","answer":"cap=cv2.VideoCapture(0); ok,frame=cap.read().","reasoning":"VideoCapture reads from camera device index 0 by default."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why check cap.isOpened() before reading?","answer":"To verify the camera resource is available.","reasoning":"If not opened, reads will fail and loops may crash."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you set camera resolution in OpenCV?","answer":"cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_WIDTH,w); cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_HEIGHT,h).","reasoning":"Properties request a resolution; actual may vary by device."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute FPS in a video loop?","answer":"fps = 1.0/(t_now - t_prev).","reasoning":"Timing deltas estimate frames per second."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you write video to disk with OpenCV?","answer":"out=cv2.VideoWriter(path,fourcc,fps,(w,h)); out.write(frame).","reasoning":"VideoWriter encodes frames into a video container."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you choose a fourcc codec in OpenCV?","answer":"fourcc=cv2.VideoWriter_fourcc(*'mp4v') or similar.","reasoning":"Codec selection depends on platform support."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you detect corners using Shi-Tomasi?","answer":"cv2.goodFeaturesToTrack(gray,maxCorners,qualityLevel,minDistance).","reasoning":"Finds strong corners for tracking features."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you track points using Lucas-Kanade optical flow?","answer":"cv2.calcOpticalFlowPyrLK(prev_gray,gray,prev_pts,None,**params).","reasoning":"LK estimates motion of sparse features between frames."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is dense optical flow in OpenCV?","answer":"Flow per-pixel rather than per-feature.","reasoning":"Dense flow estimates motion vectors for every pixel."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute Farneback dense optical flow?","answer":"cv2.calcOpticalFlowFarneback(prev,cur,None,**params).","reasoning":"Farneback provides dense motion field between grayscale frames."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you detect lines using Hough Transform?","answer":"lines=cv2.HoughLinesP(edges, rho, theta, threshold, minLineLength, maxLineGap).","reasoning":"HoughLinesP finds line segments from edge maps."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you detect circles using HoughCircles?","answer":"cv2.HoughCircles(gray, cv2.HOUGH_GRADIENT, dp, minDist, param1, param2, minRadius, maxRadius).","reasoning":"HoughCircles finds circular shapes from gradients."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you perform template matching?","answer":"res=cv2.matchTemplate(img,templ,method).","reasoning":"Template matching finds best match location of a patch."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you get best match location from template matching result?","answer":"minVal,maxVal,minLoc,maxLoc=cv2.minMaxLoc(res).","reasoning":"Pick maxLoc or minLoc depending on method."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you perform perspective transform (homography) on a document?","answer":"M=cv2.getPerspectiveTransform(src_pts,dst_pts); warped=cv2.warpPerspective(img,M,(W,H)).","reasoning":"Perspective warping rectifies planar surfaces like documents."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute a homography from matched points?","answer":"H,mask=cv2.findHomography(src_pts,dst_pts,cv2.RANSAC).","reasoning":"RANSAC rejects outliers in point correspondences."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is RANSAC used for in vision coding?","answer":"Robust model fitting with outlier rejection.","reasoning":"Common in homography and fundamental matrix estimation."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you detect ORB keypoints and descriptors?","answer":"orb=cv2.ORB_create(); kp,des=orb.detectAndCompute(gray,None).","reasoning":"ORB provides fast local features for matching."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you match ORB descriptors with BFMatcher?","answer":"bf=cv2.BFMatcher(cv2.NORM_HAMMING, crossCheck=True); matches=bf.match(des1,des2).","reasoning":"ORB uses binary descriptors, so Hamming distance is appropriate."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you sort matches by distance?","answer":"matches=sorted(matches,key=lambda m:m.distance).","reasoning":"Smaller distance means better match."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you perform KNN matching and apply ratio test?","answer":"matches=bf.knnMatch(des1,des2,k=2); keep=m for m,n in matches if m.distance < 0.75*n.distance].","reasoning":"Ratio test filters ambiguous matches and improves robustness."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you detect faces using OpenCV Haar cascades?","answer":"face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray, scaleFactor, minNeighbors).","reasoning":"Haar cascades provide classic fast detection, though less accurate than modern DNNs."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why prefer DNN-based detectors over Haar cascades?","answer":"Better accuracy and robustness.","reasoning":"DNN detectors handle pose, lighting, and variations more reliably."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you perform background subtraction using MOG2?","answer":"fg=bgsub.apply(frame).","reasoning":"Background models separate moving foreground from static background."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why apply morphological ops after background subtraction?","answer":"To remove speckle noise and fill holes.","reasoning":"Foreground masks are often noisy without cleanup."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute connected components in a binary mask?","answer":"num,labels,stats,centroids=cv2.connectedComponentsWithStats(mask).","reasoning":"Connected components label each blob and provide stats like area and bbox."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you filter connected components by area?","answer":"Keep labels where statsi,cv2.CC_STAT_AREA] >= min_area.","reasoning":"Filters out small noisy blobs."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert between xyxy and xywh for boxes?","answer":"xywh: x=x1,y=y1,w=x2-x1,h=y2-y1; xyxy: x2=x+w,y2=y+h.","reasoning":"Different APIs and overlays use different box formats."},
  
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"In OpenCV, how do you pad an image with a constant border?","answer":"cv2.copyMakeBorder(img, top, bottom, left, right, cv2.BORDER_CONSTANT, value=val).","reasoning":"Padding is common before resizing, cropping, or running models that require fixed input size."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you pad an image while preserving edge pixels (replicate)?","answer":"cv2.copyMakeBorder(img, t,b,l,r, cv2.BORDER_REPLICATE).","reasoning":"Replicate padding reduces boundary artifacts compared to constant padding."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you center-crop an image to a target width and height?","answer":"Compute center and slice: imgy0:y0+th, x0:x0+tw].","reasoning":"Center crops keep the most central content and are common in preprocessing."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you letterbox an image for detection models?","answer":"Resize with aspect ratio then pad to target size.","reasoning":"Letterboxing preserves aspect ratio and avoids distortion while fitting a fixed model input."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is the risk of resizing without preserving aspect ratio for detection?","answer":"Geometric distortion of objects.","reasoning":"Distortion can reduce model accuracy and misalign boxes."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you convert a bounding box from letterboxed coords back to original image coords?","answer":"Undo padding offsets then divide by scale factor.","reasoning":"You must reverse the preprocessing transform to map boxes correctly."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"In NumPy, how do you ensure an image array is contiguous in memory?","answer":"img = np.ascontiguousarray(img).","reasoning":"Some libraries require contiguous arrays for performance or correctness."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why can non-contiguous arrays cause issues in OpenCV or DNN inference?","answer":"Underlying C code may assume contiguous memory.","reasoning":"Strides from slicing can break expected memory layout."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you change an image dtype to float32 in NumPy?","answer":"img = img.astype(np.float32).","reasoning":"Many ML models require float32 input."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you scale float32 image back to uint8 safely?","answer":"img_u8 = np.clip(img*255.0,0,255).astype(np.uint8).","reasoning":"Clipping prevents overflow/underflow before casting."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute a histogram for each color channel in BGR?","answer":"Call cv2.calcHist per channel index 0,1,2.","reasoning":"Per-channel histograms help analyze color distributions independently."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you split and merge color channels in OpenCV?","answer":"b,g,r=cv2.split(img); img=cv2.merge(b,g,r]).","reasoning":"Splitting allows channel-specific processing."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is gamma correction and how do you apply it in Python?","answer":"Apply power-law transform: out = (img/255)^gamma * 255.","reasoning":"Gamma adjusts brightness non-linearly, improving contrast in dark or bright scenes."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you adjust image brightness and contrast in OpenCV?","answer":"out = cv2.convertScaleAbs(img, alpha=contrast, beta=brightness).","reasoning":"alpha scales contrast; beta shifts brightness."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you sharpen an image using a convolution kernel?","answer":"Use cv2.filter2D with a sharpening kernel.","reasoning":"Convolution can enhance edges by emphasizing high frequencies."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you apply a custom convolution kernel in OpenCV?","answer":"out = cv2.filter2D(img, ddepth=-1, kernel=k).","reasoning":"filter2D applies arbitrary spatial filters."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why can large convolution kernels slow down processing?","answer":"More multiplications per pixel.","reasoning":"Kernel size increases per-pixel compute cost."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute Laplacian edges in OpenCV?","answer":"lap = cv2.Laplacian(gray, cv2.CV_64F).","reasoning":"Laplacian highlights rapid intensity changes (edges)." },
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is difference between Sobel and Laplacian operators?","answer":"Sobel computes first derivatives; Laplacian computes second derivatives.","reasoning":"Second derivatives can be more sensitive to noise."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you denoise an image with Non-Local Means in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.fastNlMeansDenoising(gray, None, h, templateWindowSize, searchWindowSize).","reasoning":"NLM can preserve textures better than simple blurs."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you denoise a color image with Non-Local Means?","answer":"cv2.fastNlMeansDenoisingColored(img, None, hColor, hLuma, templateWindowSize, searchWindowSize).","reasoning":"Colored variant handles chroma and luma components."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute image gradients using Scharr operator?","answer":"cv2.Scharr(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0) or (0,1).","reasoning":"Scharr provides better rotational symmetry than Sobel for small kernels."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you normalize a gradient image for display?","answer":"norm = cv2.normalize(grad, None, 0, 255, cv2.NORM_MINMAX).astype(np.uint8).","reasoning":"Gradients can be negative and wide-range; normalize to 0..255."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute a binary mask from edges?","answer":"Use thresholding on edges or directly use edges as mask.","reasoning":"Canny output is already binary-like (0 or 255)."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you find the largest contour by area?","answer":"largest = max(contours, key=cv2.contourArea).","reasoning":"Selecting the biggest blob is common for document or object segmentation."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute convex hull for a contour?","answer":"hull = cv2.convexHull(cnt).","reasoning":"Convex hull approximates outer boundary and is used in shape analysis."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute contour solidity?","answer":"solidity = area / hull_area.","reasoning":"Solidity distinguishes compact shapes from concave shapes."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute moments of a contour?","answer":"M = cv2.moments(cnt).","reasoning":"Moments are used to compute centroids and other shape properties."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute the centroid from contour moments?","answer":"cx = M'm10']/M'm00']; cy = M'm01']/M'm00'] if m00!=0.","reasoning":"m00 is area; division yields centroid coordinates."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute an ellipse fit for a contour?","answer":"ellipse = cv2.fitEllipse(cnt) if len(cnt)>=5.","reasoning":"Ellipse fitting requires enough points and is useful for circular/oval objects."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you draw an ellipse in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.ellipse(img, ellipse, color, thickness).","reasoning":"Visualizes fitted ellipses for shape inspection."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute bounding box IoU in Python?","answer":"Compute intersection area and union area from xyxy boxes.","reasoning":"IoU is core to NMS, tracking, and evaluation."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why must you guard against negative intersection sizes in IoU?","answer":"Boxes may not overlap.","reasoning":"Intersection width/height should be max(0, ...) to avoid negative areas."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you compute intersection rectangle of two xyxy boxes?","answer":"ix1=max(x1a,x1b); iy1=max(y1a,y1b); ix2=min(x2a,x2b); iy2=min(y2a,y2b).","reasoning":"Intersection corners are formed by max of starts and min of ends."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you implement simple NMS in Python?","answer":"Sort by score, keep highest, remove boxes with IoU>thr iteratively.","reasoning":"NMS reduces duplicate detections for the same object."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"What is the difference between NMS and Soft-NMS?","answer":"NMS removes boxes; Soft-NMS decays scores.","reasoning":"Soft-NMS can improve recall for crowded scenes."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you create a blank image canvas in NumPy?","answer":"canvas = np.zeros((h,w,3), dtype=np.uint8).","reasoning":"Useful for synthetic tests and drawing."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you draw a rectangle in OpenCV?","answer":"cv2.rectangle(img,(x1,y1),(x2,y2),color,thickness).","reasoning":"Rectangles are used for boxes, ROIs, and UI overlays."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you draw a filled rectangle?","answer":"Use thickness=-1.","reasoning":"Negative thickness fills shapes in OpenCV."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you draw a circle and control thickness?","answer":"cv2.circle(img,(cx,cy),r,color,thickness).","reasoning":"Circles are useful for keypoints and targets."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you draw a line between two points?","answer":"cv2.line(img,(x1,y1),(x2,y2),color,thickness).","reasoning":"Line overlays visualize trajectories and boundaries."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you put text on an image?","answer":"cv2.putText(img,text,(x,y),font,scale,color,thickness).","reasoning":"Labels provide human-readable overlays for detections."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"Why might cv2.putText look jagged and how to improve it?","answer":"Use lineType=cv2.LINE_AA.","reasoning":"Anti-aliased text improves visual quality."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you measure blur using variance of Laplacian?","answer":"score = cv2.Laplacian(gray, cv2.CV_64F).var().","reasoning":"Lower variance often indicates blur and can gate frame quality."},
  {"course":"computer_vision_coding","question":"How do you implement a blur threshold gate in a video pipeline?","answer":"If blur_score < thr: skip frame or warn.","reasoning":"Quality gating reduces false detections from blurry frames."},
