  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"In rclpy, why must you call rclpy.init() before creating any Node?","answer":"It initializes the ROS 2 client library and DDS resources.","reasoning":"Without init, the middleware is not ready and node creation/communication can fail."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is the correct shutdown sequence for a basic rclpy node?","answer":"destroy_node() then rclpy.shutdown().","reasoning":"Destroying the node releases handles; shutdown tears down ROS client resources."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What does rclpy.spin(node) do in a Python node?","answer":"Processes callbacks until shutdown.","reasoning":"Spin runs the executor loop that dispatches timers, subscriptions, services, and actions."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"What is the default executor used by rclpy.spin?","answer":"SingleThreadedExecutor.","reasoning":"By default, callbacks execute sequentially in one thread."},
  {"course":"ros2_coding","question":"How do you create a publisher in rclpy?","answer":"pub = node.create_publisher(MsgType, 'topic', qos_depth).","reasoning":"Publishers require message type, topic name, and QoS."},
